NEW AIR SERVICE
IS INAUGURATED
Canton-Shanghai Link Regarded
As Forerunner Of Line To
Philippines Soon
By United Press
SHANGHAI,
Oct.
24.-A
new
and vitally important link in the
aerial conquest of the Pacific was
forged today when the China Na-
tional Aviation Company formally
inaugurated its
Shanghai-Canton
air mail service, thus marking an-
other step towards the establish-
ment of regular service between
the United States and the Philip-
pin.es.
Plans for the trans-Pacific ser-
vice are making rapid
progress
under the direction of H. M. Bix-
by, one of the daring little group
of St. Louis businessmen who fin-
anced the historic flight of Colonel
Charles A. Lindbergh from
New
York to Paris and
now a vice-
president of
Pan-American Air-
ways, working in cooperation with
executives of the China National
Aviation Corporation,
in
which
the Pan-American and the Chinese
National Government are partners.
Bixby is presently in Manila ne-
gotiating for the franchise with
the Philippine legislature for the
service from Hongkong to Manila.
The inauguration of the Shang-
hai-Canton air mail
line took
place with the departure from the
Lunghwa airport here at 6:02 o'-
clock this morning of the giant Si-
korsky amphibian plane for
Can-
ton.
The plane carried 500 letters
and packages and was piloted by
R. H. Gast, with H. Woods as co-
pilot.
W. S. Grooch, manager of
the China National Aviation Com-
pany, was aboard.
At 9:30 a. m. the plane passed
over Wenchow.
The Sikorsky was scheduled to
arrive at Canton at 5 o'clock this
afternoon. It will lie over at Can-
ton until 2:30 p. m.
tomorrow,
when it will leave for Swatow, ar-
riving at that city at 5:20 p. m.
and leaving there at 6:15 a. m. on
October 26,
reaching Shanghai
again at 3 p. m. of the same day.
The new service will assure re-
ceivers of air mail at Canton that
theit replies wested ay, can on at
Shanghai on Thursday afternoon,
The second schedule of each
week will be started from Shang-
hai on Friday morning, the plane
returning to this city on Saturday
afternoon.
During the first 30 days of its
operation the line will carry mails
only, thus giving the company an
opportunity to make arrangements
for the handling of passengers at
the various points, which will re-
quire the the installation of a wide
variety of facilities.
No arrangement has at the pres-
ent time been concluded for land-
ing at Hongkong.
